.SH NAME
sysopctl \- A custom Linux command for managing system resources and tasks.

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sysopctl
[\fB--help\fR] [\fB--version\fR] \fIcommand\fR [\fIoptions\fR] [\fIarguments\fR]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B sysopctl
is a versatile system administration utility designed to streamline the management of system resources, services, processes, and overall system health. This tool offers a user-friendly interface for performing common administrative tasks efficiently.

.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B service list
Display a list of all active services currently running on the system.

.TP
.B service start <service-name>
Initiate the specified service.

.TP
.B service stop <service-name>
Terminate the specified service.

.TP
.B system load
Show the current system load averages to monitor performance.

.TP
.B disk usage
Display disk usage statistics for each partition.

.TP
.B process monitor
Observe and monitor system processes in real-time.

.TP
.B logs analyze
Analyze and review recent critical log entries for system health checks.

.TP
.B backup <path>
Create a backup of system files from the specified path.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B --help
Output help information for using the command.

.TP
.B --version
Output version information for the tool.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B sysopctl service list
Displays all active system services currently running.

.TP
.B sysopctl service start apache2
Starts the `apache2` service.

.TP
.B sysopctl service stop apache2
Stops the `apache2` service.

.TP
.B sysopctl system load
Displays the current load averages of the system.

.TP
.B sysopctl disk usage
Shows disk usage statistics for all partitions.

.TP
.B sysopctl process monitor
Initiates real-time monitoring of system processes.

.TP
.B sysopctl logs analyze
Analyzes and displays recent critical log entries.

.TP
.B sysopctl backup /home/user
Creates a backup of the `/home/user` directory.

